Student Spotlight: There was a very heavy rainfall at the beginning of Friday night's varsity football game. The President of the Glen Rose Athletic Booster Club was taking photos of the game, but took shelter under the band bleachers to protect his camera from the rain. Gatesville High School student, Aandon Hafercamp, gave this gentleman his jacket so he could protect his camera from the rain.

The Booster President messaged us the following, "What a tremendous act of kindness for which I am very appreciative. I had a Glen Rose shirt on so he knew I was a guest. It's apparent that young man has been taught well at home and at school on how to treat others. If the simple actions of one are indicative of the actions of all the members of your band, you have a great group of young men and young women."

Aandon is the son of David and Sandra Christian. Please help us thank Aandon on representing our school and community in such an outstanding way!

post_text: Staff Recognition: On Friday after our students had dismissed from school, custodial staff members Brian Reeder and Kenneth Arrington noticed a man trying to break into a faculty member's vehicle. After confronting the suspect, they called for help and followed the suspect as he fled. Athletic Director Rickey Phillips quickly placed the high school gym on lockdown to protect the athletes and fans. Maintenance Director Toby Williams and School Resource Officer Damian White subdued the suspect. Because of their quick thinking and courageous acts, everyone remained safe. Please help us thank these outstanding GISD staff members.

post_text:
This past spring, several of our 7th grade student students challenged the ACT exam as part of the Duke TIP program. The ACT is used as a college entrance exam.

Because of their high scores, the following students qualified for the eStudies and Summer Studies through the Duke TIP program: Hannah Bartlett, Jeret Burks, Levi Cuellar, John Davidson, Alexander Johnson, Jahziel Martinez, Vania Martinez, Dutch Nielsen, Gabriel Pollard, and Jaycee Shelton.

Gabriel Pollard also qualified for the State Recognition, while Jeret Burks qualified for the State Recognition and the Grand Recognition. All of these students (who are now 8th graders) had scores similar to high school students across the nation who are trying to gain entrance to college. Congratulations to these students for such a big accomplishment!!!

post_text:
On Friday, September 4, at 7:15 p.m., GISD is going to dedicate "Tommy Davidson Field" before the home football game against Glen Rose. McKamie Stadium is retaining its name, so the official title will be Tommy Davidson Field at McKamie Stadium.

Tommy is the son of Cotton and Carolyn Davidson. He was an outstanding athlete and a 1974 graduate of Gatesville High School. He played football at Baylor University and returned to Gatesville to practice chiropractics. Tommy and his wife Nina had three children: Casey, Claire, and Will. He went on to serve on the Gatesville City Council and Gatesville ISD School Board. He served for many years as an athletic trainer to Gatesville High School.

More recently, he served as the team chiropractor for Baylor University athletics. Tragically, Dr. Davidson passed away in October of 2019 from injuries sustained in a traffic accident. This was one small way to honor a long-time servant of GISD and the Gatesville community.

If your student is enrolling in a dual credit course at the high school, please contact Nadine Webber, the CTC representative. She will go through the online registration process with you. She will also explain the process of the practice TSI for placement into the dual credit classes. Once the actual TSI can be administered, students will be required to take it. Please email her at NWebber@ctcd.edu to get those processes started as well as any CTC questions you may have.

In addition to that, please come get paperwork from the high school to enroll in those classes. Packets can be picked up in the main office & must be returned with all signatures. The counselors will then scan & email the completed packets to Ms. Webber. Please contact the HS campus with any other questions.

post_text: We want to thank our parents for responding to the back-to-school survey. Remember, the survey is not "binding," and parents may certainly change their minds as the start of school approaches. Of 2,015 parent responses, 69.1% opted for traditional in-person instruction, 23.2% chose remote virtual instruction, and another 7.6% selected the hybrid model of mainly remote instruction with attendance in the UIL class periods and practice. If you have not submitted a survey, you may continue to respond to the survey.

post_text:
"Doing what is best for kids" has been GISD's slogan for many years. That phrase was coined by Dr. Willie Clarke (1948-2013), who served on the GISD school board from 1984 to 1987. Reverend Clarke served as pastor of Sweet Home Missionary Baptist Church here in Gatesville for 20 years. Valedictorian of his high school class with countless advanced degrees, Dr. Clarke knew the importance of education.

A powerful preacher with a fantastic singing voice, Willie was a pillar of our community for decades. Humble, kind, genuine, soft-spoken, and caring are just a few words to describe Dr. Clarke. He and his faithful wife, Robbie, are missed greatly.

In recognition of his service, Dr. Pollard has asked the City to proclaim September 9th (Willie's birthday) as Willie Clarke Day (Reverend Clarke also served on the Gatesville City Council from 2000-2002 and President of the Gatesville Chamber of Commerce). Mayor Chumley enthusiastically supported the idea. Thank you and we miss you, Rev. Clarke.

post_text:
By now you have probably seen the guidance from TEA regarding the return to school in the fall. While many GISD staff members had already been working diligently on a local plan, it was important to finally receive guidance from the state.

Of course, the state's plan may have left you with more questions or concerns. It will take time to address all of the directives in the state's plan, but GISD is working quickly to provide a practical plan that focuses on the health of the students and staff.

GISD will be sending a survey to all parents to gain more information from you. However, because the covid situation is so fluid, the survey will likely go out in a couple of weeks so that the information gained is as accurate as possible right before the start of school.

Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) is a one-time food benefit for families who lost access to free or reduced-price meals due to school closures. Eligible P-EBT families will receive application instructions in their children's report cards which will be mailed later this week.

The P-EBT application will open the first week of June.
P-EBT food benefits are for children who received SNAP food benefits for March 2020 and children who are certified for free or reduced-price school meals during the 2019-20 Texas school year. For more information, visit: hhs.texas.gov/PEBT

In addition to the Classroom Teachers of the Year, our staff also voted on the Employee of the Year for each campus and department. These staff members are extremely hard working and come to work each day with a fantastic attitude.

The Employees of the Year are: Tammy Brown (PR), Betty Cooper (EL), Chelsea Campbell and Mike Reeder (IN), April Clark and Michelle Byrd (JH), Sheryl Lovejoy (HS), Ray Fread (Maintenance), Pam Rueter (Transportation), and Margaret Ely (Nutrition). Please help us congratulate these wonderful employees.

GISD is pleased to announce several faculty and staff awards. First, because of their dedication and commitment to our students, our five school resource officers (SROs) and our five campus cafeteria managers are receiving the "Above and Beyond Award."

Our five SROs are Damian White, Kris Smith, Sid Post, Gary Stiles, and Carol Brown. Our five cafeteria managers are Tammy Brown, Betty Cooper, Loraine Watson, Mike Campbell, and Charlotte Brandstetter. Please help us congratulate these very hard-working and deserving employees.

post_text:
Gatesville ISD has partnered with Tarleton State University through its Distinguished High School Partnership Program. In this new program, GISD students who graduate in the top 25% of their class receive automatic admission to Tarleton.

For students in the top 10% of their class, Tarleton will be adding $1,000 to their annual scholarship awards, while students in the top 25% of their class will receive an additional $500 to their annual scholarship amounts.

The administration at Tarleton noted that Gatesville graduates historically perform very well at Tarleton. Way to go Gatesville grads!!!

post_text:
GISD is proud to announce the top two graduates of the Class of 2020. David Bryan (pictured left) is valedictorian and Mason Edwards (pictured right) is salutatorian. Both of these young men have achieved so much in their school careers that their accomplishments are too numerous to list here. However, a few are listed below.

David was a regional qualifier in UIL science in both his sophomore and junior years as well as a regional qualifier in UIL number sense in his junior year. David scored a 1570 out of 1600 on the SAT. Mason is currently Class President, Student Council President, and National Honor Society President. He placed 4th in the Lincoln-Douglas Debate District UIL Competition.

Both of these young men are Eagle Scouts and wonderful representatives of our community. Please join us in congratulating these two outstanding GHS students.

post_text:
Governor Greg Abbott has closed schools across the state of Texas for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year. Commissioner of Education Mike Morath will be giving school districts additional guidance on graduation ceremony options.

The GISD administrative team had already been developing alternate plans for many end-of-year processes. After next week's board meeting, we will be communicating plans for graduation, the fate of prom, course registration for next year, senior scholarships, retrieving personal items from the campuses, awards, and summer school.

We know our families are anxious to have some finality to these items, so we appreciate your continued patience as we also try to meet constantly updated state and federal expectations.

We want to wish everyone a happy and safe Easter weekend. In observance of the Easter holiday (Good Friday through Easter Sunday), we have asked our staff to pause any educational activities during that time. Conversely, our teachers may not respond with answers to questions until Monday.

One other update: The Primary campus parking lot facing the football stadium now has wifi access (GISD Visitor) for those with devices needing Internet. We ask that you remain in your vehicle to observe social distaning guidelines.

post_text:
With Gatesville residents having possible exposure to COVID-19 at a local workplace, GISD wants to minimize the possible spread of this illness. Therefore, school will be closed next week (March 16-20). We will re-evaluate the situation later next week.

The state has declared that districts closing school offer "some degree of instructional support while students are at home." So, parents and students may receive communication from their campuses or teachers regarding some light work that could be completed at home.

GISD will still offer breakfast, lunch, and evening meals for students who are interested. Much like the summer feeding program, school nutrition personnel will be stationed at the Primary and Elementary Campus parking lots. Students in any grade may go to either of those locations at 8:00 a.m., 12:00 noon, or 4:00 p.m. to receive a grab-and-go sack meal.

We hope everyone continues to be healthy and safe.

With Gatesville residents having possible exposure to COVID-19 at a local workplace, GISD wants to minimize the possible spread of this illness. Therefore, school will be closed next week (March 16-20). We will re-evaluate the situation later next week.

GISD will still offer breakfast, lunch, and evening meals for students who are interested. post_text:
Coronavirus update: Most of you probably know that a confirmed case of COVID-19 has been found in Bell County. That person worked at Laerdal in Gatesville.

GISD has been closely monitoring the COVID-19 situation. We have a safety plan in place. Governor Abbott held a press conference at noon giving all of us more guidance. We have met with Coryell Health officials as well as representatives from the County. In addition, superintendents in Coryell County will be meeting today at 2:00 p.m. Commissioner of Education, Mike Morath, will be giving more guidance to schools this afternoon at 3:00 p.m.

The maintenance and custodial crews will be conducting a deep clean of the campuses this weekend. Our main goal is to ensure the health of our students and staff. We are trying to be cautious and make decisions in the best interests of our GISD families, while also not reacting out of fear or panic. This is a fluid situation, so no final decisions have been made yet regarding school on Monday. We will inform all of you as quickly as possible once any decisions are made.

post_text: Recently, the junior high and high school campuses hosted one of the most captivating speakers we have ever had. Lieutenant James Thomas with the Texas Rangers has had an illustrious career. He has conducted high risk search warrants, served in the anti-gang center in Houston, and was appointed as a Special Deputy US Marshal with the Gulf Coast Violent Offenders and Fugitive Task Force. He holds a doctoral degree and is a FBI LEEDA Trilogy Award recipient. Thank you James for being an outstanding role model and keeping the citizens of Texas safe!

post_text: Law Enforcement officials with the Attorney General’s office notified Gatesville ISD that one of its employees, a custodian, had been arrested on charges of “possession of lewd visual material depicting a child.” According to law enforcement, the inappropriate material was viewed on a personal device at this individual’s home. Although no inappropriate activity occurred on school property, this is an extremely serious charge. The employee was placed on leave while the investigation continues. We do not have any other details at this time, but Gatesville ISD will continue to work closely with law enforcement.
